"Sound Genetics" allows brain cells to be controlled by sound waves
The video shows how the shuttleworms change direction as soon as the sound impulse hits them.
Scientists have grown worms with genetically modified nerve systems to be controlled by sound wave bursts.
The tiny shuttleworms change direction as soon as they are hit by a sound impulse that is too high to be heard by the human ear.
The impulses work by turning on genetically modified motion nerve cells with membrane channels that react to ultrasound waves.
Related: Scientists Read and Write Brain Activity with Light
The researchers said that worms show the effectiveness of a new method called sound genetics, in which ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure whereby electrical impulses are introduced into people’s brains to treat Parkinson’s disease.
Spaceworms do not normally react to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles amplified the ultrasound waves, which then pass into the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect the TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
To produce ultrasound-controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motion nerve cells have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they switch on the modified motion nerve cells.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn on and off nerve cells using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which needs to be sent along the optical fiber to the desired point inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it may be possible to have the targeted human nerve cells momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
