Eurozone inflation declined to 0.1 per cent in August
Consumer prices in the euro area rose only 0.1 per cent year-on-year in August, the EU's statistical authority, Eurostat, said today.
The rise in prices was driven down by lower energy prices.
Eurostat thus revised its forecast of 0.2% a few weeks ago slightly downwards.
In July, the inflation rate was 0.2%.
The so-called base inflation fell to 0.9 per cent in August from 1.0 per cent in July.
Eurostat’s forecast for baseline inflation was 1.0 per cent.
Last month, energy in the euro area was 7.2 per cent cheaper than a year ago.
In the whole of the 28 EU countries, average inflation was zero in August.
In July, the increase was 0.1 per cent.
Among the euro countries, consumer prices rose by 1.4 per cent in Malta in August.
In Cyprus, inflation was at its lowest when prices fell by 1.9 %.
In Finland, inflation was 0.2% minus according to the EU harmonised price index.
Inflation in the euro area remains persistently far from the European Central Bank’s (ECB) target of a price increase of around 2% over the medium term.
The ECB forecasts an average inflation rate of 0.1% for the euro area this year.
The rise will pick up to 1.1 per cent next year, the central bank predicts in its new inflation forecasts published in early September.
The U.S. Fed is trying to tighten monetary policy.
The next U.S. recession will start at its fastest in less than a year, but more likely in three years after the Fed starts raising its interest rates again.
In the financial markets, the downturn begins before the next downturn.
The Fed has suggested it will start raising interest rates this week and at the latest by the end of the year.
Thus, the next recession may hit its fastest by next autumn, and the financial markets will rhythm before that.
Or at least that is what will happen if the world’s largest economy and financial markets operate as they used to – and if they react to the Fed’s extortion of money faucets as they have done in the past.
These are the conclusions of Deutsche Bank’s London market research strategists Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed a 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study to its international large customers last week.
The study and the report do not pretend to know exactly when the Fed will raise its interest rates or what will happen in the economy and markets afterwards.
Instead, they use cool facts and calculations to present economic statistics on how the economy and markets have behaved in the past during and after the Fed’s interest rate increases.
In addition to historical observations, they look at which key variables in the economy and financial markets are now in the same or another pattern as at the time of previous interest rate increases – and what the consequences may be.
It is clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in a more fragile position to withstand the rise in interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
The beginning of the recession may not be a year.
The leaders deciding on the Fed’s monetary policy and its current tune have been insinuating throughout last summer and early autumn that the time is ripe for raising interest rates.
The first increase in interest rates in over nine years can be expected this week.
The matter will be resolved on Wednesday and Thursday, when the so-called Open Market Committee of the Fed Board meets to decide on the matter at its two-day meeting.
The Fed raised its Fed Funds interest rate in June 2006.
That ended exactly two years of relatively regular but small 0.25 percentage point increases, with the Fed raising interest rates from 1.25% to 5.25%.
The financial symptomatology began in 2007 with the difficulties of the most risky housing financing in the United States, and a year later the financial crisis torn into a global doomsday nightmare.
There was a major recession in 2009.
Last time, the severe hardships in the financial markets and the real economy began at a slower pace than has typically been the case since the previous Fed interest rate increases.
Similarly, the trials were harsher and harsher than they have been since the recession in the 1930s.
Deutsche’s strategists have been screening the rises and declines of the world’s largest economies and the turning points of the financial markets since 1950 and in places since the early 19th century.
The Fed’s interest rate increases and their economic and financial impacts have been reported since the 1950s.
At its fastest, it has taken less than a year, in most cases less than three years and on average less than three and a half years, to start the recession.
The rise in the financial market has ended within one to two years of the Fed’s interest rate increases.
Since the beginning of the 1950s, the Fed has raised and lowered its interest rate for a dozen cycles of different lengths.
Each time has been different in some respects, and the multiplier is relatively scarce in the review, so it is hardly possible to draw any definite conclusions on the effects of subsequent interest rate increases.
It reminds me that this time a lot of things are different.
And not just better.
Heels too low for too long
The decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, may not be unquestionably determined even by decades of research.
But three things about the causes that led to the crisis and increased its destructive power are probably somewhat clear:
1) In the 21st century, the Fed, the ECB and other major central banks in the world considered their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched the techno bubble's tracks, and they raised the next one.
2) The accumulated and already excessive amount of debt in different parts of the financial and real economy over the decades increased even more as a result of the monetary policy of central banks overlapping.
It was the largest debt bubble in economic history.
3) Especially the insanely cheap debt financing, which was packed into the financial economy almost without any restraint, inflated the largest bubbles in the history of the financial market, from shares to real estate, bonds and commodities.
It is also unlikely that there will be a very harsh dispute that the financial markets, relying on ever more complex leverage, were in an extremely dangerous and unstable state of affairs when the Fed and other central banks last pushed interest rates upwards.
The financial structures tuned to the leverage of debt, let alone the valuation bubbles, did not last longer than their time, after interest rate increases had begun and the cost of debt financing had started to rise.
The risks materialised as a financial crisis, followed by a major recession.
Bigger bubbles and more debt
The German strategists do not speculate on what will happen next, but they give reason to think about things such as:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary stance even lighter for longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low before the crisis for too long, they have now been even lower for even longer.
2) Debt has not been cheaper for a long time than it was ten years ago, but now debt is literally cheaper at its cheapest than free.
Thus, the debt burden of the financial and real economy has not eased, but is now heavier than before or at any time before the financial crisis in different parts of the economy.
3) Liquidity issued by central banks, which has become more fluid and cheaper, has largely remained in the financial markets and has slowed key securities and assets to their highest levels since the peak before the financial crisis or at any time.
And not only do the strategists have a latitudinal atmosphere with warning signs on the financial markets, but they also point out that even the US economy has not yet recovered from the financial crisis and the worst recession in decades, as it has done in the past.
The euro area economy has hardly recovered.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak state, but correspondingly, the pressures and risks on the financial markets are incomparably greater than before the financial crisis, when the Fed next begins to tighten its money faucets more tightly.
Perhaps the future of Albert Edwards, the strategist of the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it may seem.
He has been coaching the bank’s international investor clients for the following Fed turnarounds for quite some time:
First, the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst - and soon it's time for the Fed to rush to extinguish the financial flames with even bigger QE money sprays.
