This week, the Federal Reserve will sit for two days around a huge mahogany table at a long-awaited meeting to decide whether it is time to raise the interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative, two-storey meeting room is a mural from the United States.
The map is a reminder that the President of the Central Bank, Janet L. Yellen, and his colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation first.
Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the central bank’s shoulders: to maximize employment in the United States and to keep prices stable.
After the Great Depression, however, the governors of the central bank have accepted that there is also a third unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is precisely this third requirement that can be the decisive factor in a decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so tight that it cannot even be predicted, a decision on whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record incentive brought by the near-zero short-term interest rates until the end of 2008.
While most of the data shows that the economy is growing steadily, the recent turmoil in the global financial markets may have made central bank officials, who are already on the lookout, more alarmed when it comes to increasing instability. There are fears about how it would affect if the federal fund rate reference value were raised by at least a quarter of a percentage point.
“Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important factors to be monitored,” says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial expert at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"I believe, however, that if they are looking for a justification for keeping interest rates unchanged, then increased uncertainty in the global market is a valid enough reason to wait," he said.
There has been no consensus on the central bank’s decision, which in itself creates nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent Bloomberg study, about half of economists predict interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the withdrawal, as according to the key indicator, the potential for growth is only about 30%.
This implies a decline in the securities market if the central bank raises the level, unless policy makers then manage to mitigate the shock by promising that the next withdrawal will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average Index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4 per cent, a new figure of 16,599.85.
The recovery was accompanied by the expectation that the central bank would maintain the level this week, says John Lonski, chief financial expert at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It’s surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now,” he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, “they will have to put a lot of effort into their policies to support the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argue that a higher level would calm the financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, the central bank seemed to be raising interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation, which would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year, despite the fact that the Liberals are calling for more economic development in their complaints.
While job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell last month to 5.1%, the lowest rate in seven years and close to what the central bank sees as the limit for full employment.
Increases in wages have shown signs of recovery.
Although inflation remains below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, the main reason for this is, according to the central bank’s decision-makers, the temporary effect of a significant drop in oil prices.
The economy “survives and needs higher interest rates in view of the tight labour market conditions,” says Ian Shepherdson, chief economics expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world shook last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by up to 16 percent from its May record, as investors feared China’s slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now almost 10 percent below its peak in May.
For central bank policymakers, market turmoil is an additional factor in the complex equation that tells when interest rates need to be raised.
“Without these financial market events and the news of recent weeks about the weakness of China’s economy, policy makers would tighten the standard at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate Specialist and former central bank official.
Now he predicts that decision makers will wait at least a month to get a better understanding of the impact.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still quite unclear and they have little information at their disposal regarding the consequences of the events in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not a central bank's main concern, so in principle it should not affect decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the Central Bank has been enormous.
In 2013, the insinuation by the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, that the central bank could “reduce” the amount of money added, caused upheavals in the markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more art than science,” says Zachary Karabell, Head of Global Strategy at Envestnet Inc., an asset management company.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that “in the past, the central bank has overreacted to financial market movements that seem to have been separated from the fundamentals of the economy.”
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for an increase in interest rates, and Lacker, a member of the committee with the right to vote, refers to the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its reference value by 0.75 percentage points during three meetings, "despite its limited, recognisable impact on U.S. economic growth," Lacker said.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only give priority to financial stability during a major crisis, as the market collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s Interest Rate Commission.
The latest turmoil is not even close to its level, Posen says.
"No one wants to be in a situation where there is fear of interest rate increases because the market is getting upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention financial stability, and as long as this is the case, I do not think that they should anticipate it.
