Weight loss surgery can help mildly obese diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last for at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are treated by other means than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get the mortality data," notes Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgeon who wrote an editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
Bariatric surgery uses various methods to reduce the size of the abdomen.
They reduce hunger and limit food absorption.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but the majority of subjects in the study have been morbidly obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
The BMI, or weight to height ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If your BMI is over 25, it indicates that you are overweight, and if your BMI is over 30, you are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric reduction, with medications for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of surgical patients decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of those who were treated by other means than surgery remained roughly the same in 29 subjects.
Of the surgical patients, 36% had a complete cure and 28% had a partial cure.
In comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes improved completely by only 1% and partially by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, as well as the "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group," the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients’ blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels over the long term.
The haemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers wrote.
Postoperative haemoglobin A1c levels fell from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the drug treatment group, it remained stable at around 8%.
This better “glycemic control,” described by improved haemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, says lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, compared with the group undergoing gastric surgery to reduce the weight, the group undergoing gastric bypass surgery had lost more weight (17.7 and 14.2 kg), had lowered their BMI more (7.4 and 5.1), had lowered their haemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1% and 2.1%), and was more likely to have achieved complete diabetes remission (46,
The University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix's Blackstone says that while the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research findings in Sweden where surgery led to longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese patients undergoing weight loss surgery were 29 percent less likely to die within a 15-year period when compared with a group who had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study does not show any improvement in surgical survival, Blackstone says the results are nevertheless encouraging for people with a BMI of less than 35 and who are interested in surgery.
“The findings are decisive precisely because they show that surgery is safe for a group with a lower body mass index,” he says, “and is not associated with an increased risk of death or kidney disease.”
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when the patient’s BMI is between 27 and 30.
“I think we wait too long before we take this seriously,” he says.
I believe that once a person has collected these genetic changes that will permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it will be very difficult to reverse the situation.
