In the last four years, ingestion of hand disinfectant by children has increased fourfold
Poisoning centers across the United States have reported a nearly 400% increase in the ingestion of highly alcoholic hand disinfectant in children under 12 years of age since 2010, according to the Georgian Poison Center.
According to Gaylord Lopez, head of the Georgia Poison Center, the number of cases of ingestion of disinfectant reported to poisoning centers in children under the age of 12 increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16117 in 2014.
"Children are more interested in these products and unfortunately a certain percentage of them are on call," Lopez told CNN.
He said some children drink disinfectant on purpose, while others want to impress their friends or respond to a challenge on social media.
There are videos on YouTube where teenagers drink disinfectant to get low-cost booze.
According to reports, teenagers have mixed disinfectant with an alcoholic mouthwash to get a stronger drink.
Pleasant disinfectant smells can attract younger children.
"The child doesn't think this is bad for him," Lopez said.
Many of the most interesting (hand dish) are those with added fragrance.
There are strawberry, grape and orange-scented disinfectants that are very attractive to children.
Hand disinfectant can contain anything between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, alcohol poisoning requires only a few injections.
"It's really concentrated alcohol," Dr. Stephen Thornton, director of medical care at the University of Kansas Poison Center, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So please don’t leave a whiskey shot lying on the table, but hand disinfectant is left in sight, and if children are interested in it, it’s a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell is a six-year-old girl who recently swallowed only four squirts of strawberry-scented hand disinfectant at school and was taken to an emergency room to be treated.
Her blood alcohol level was .179, which is twice as high as the limit for drunken driving in adults, says Chris Ritchey, an emergency medical doctor who treated the girl at the Gwinnet Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah mossed while speaking and was unable to walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors followed her overnight in a separate children's hospital for possible symptoms of brain injury, as alcohol caused her to fall and hit her head, Ritchey said.
"It was really scary," Nhaijah's mother, Ortoria Scott, told CNN.
This could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez has recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic products or disinfectant wipes and remove the disinfectant from the reach of children.
