Xi calls for broader opening of the economy to the world
The economy must be more open to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with steering the reform on Tuesday.
"China should commit to attract foreign funding and expertise and develop a policy of openness," he said at the 16th meeting of the Group on Deepening General Reform.
Supporting openness while pushing reforms forward will increase new movement and vitality, and create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Management Group adopted a series of guidelines, which include a negative list of restrictions on market access, a loosening of border control principles, a call for state-owned companies to seize private capital, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created, identifying the sectors and companies in which investment is not allowed.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant, as it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensure a legally based business environment and make the market more transparent.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, ensuring that companies decide for themselves how they conduct their business.
The opinion also stated that China would allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
In order to open up state-controlled sectors to private investors, more sectors will be opened up.
"The government will not change its stance on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent residence permits for foreigners, "green carden", will be facilitated by optimising requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed guaranteeing the professional rights of lawyers and supporting professional judges and prosecutors.
Prime Minister Li Keqiang and senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement published after the meeting.
